lol it was already explained to you NOT to use playerid. All of the code in the [b:edu309n7]with &lt;#player#&gt;[/b:edu309n7] will cause userid to refer to #player#'s userid. If it is not in the with statement, then it will refer to the player that typed it in. You shouldn't even need $name(#player#)$ at all. Simply use #@player# and it will give you the player's alias (name). You will need the playerid variable to reflect the [b:edu309n7]attacker's[/b:edu309n7] id if the attack variable is refering to the attacker's strength or something.This code should work. To make it easier to code you should use attack as a property. I'll change that. The additional code you wanted added will work if the attack property of Squiggle (set at init or otherwise) is 10000 or whatever. Do this with:
[code:edu309n7]
if &#40; $name&#40;%userid%&#41;$ = Squiggle &#41; then property &lt;Squiggle; attack=9999&gt;
[/code:edu309n7]
Put that in the player init.
Change all playerid's to userid. As long as the #player# has a variable attack, you should be safe. So with everything, this is:
[code:edu309n7]
command &lt;/a #@player#&gt; if property &lt;#quest&#46;currentroom&#91;userid&#93;#; pkon&gt; then &#123;
      set numeric &lt;playerid; %userid%&gt; 
      with &lt;#player#&gt; &#123;
         dec &lt;hp&#91;userid&#93;; $objectproperty&#40;$name&#40;%playerid%&#41;$&gt; 
         if &#40; %hp&#91;userid&#93;% &lt;= 0 &#41; then &#123; 
            msg &lt;|bYOU HAVE DIED|xb&gt; 
            goto &lt;Carbralos Tavern&gt; 
            set numeric &lt;hp&#91;userid&#93;; 100&gt; 
         &#125; 
         else msg &lt;You were attacked and have lost 7 HP&#46;&gt; 
      &#125; 
      msg &lt;You attacked #@player# for |b7|xb HP&#46;&gt; 
   &#125; 
   else msg &lt;|bYou cant attack here!|xb&gt;
[/code:edu309n7]
If you want it otherwise, I'm sure you can code it yourself.

Also, you wouldn't be using %attack[userid% since it's not a variable. It's a property, remember? So you would use #$name(%userid%)$:attack# which will give you the attack property of the character that the script is refering to (either the player who typed the command, or the player indicated in a "with" command). That should help out. I'm at school now, so I can't test the code.

You forgot to add this to the player startscript&#058;


[code:2rkunfuw]
if &#40; $name&#40;%userid%&#41;$ = Squiggle &#41; or &#40; $name&#40;%userid%&#41;$ = TheNobleOne &#41; then &#123;
property &lt;$name&#40;%userid%&#41;$;attack=9993&gt;
&#125;
else &#123;
property &lt;$name&#40;%userid%&#41;$;attack=7&gt;
&#125;
[/code:2rkunfuw]

I think these are the proper commands. I don't have any reference to check, but I think it's right.

REMEMBER: attack is no longer a numeric variable. It's a property.
